      <hedline>
        <hl1>Therapists in Court</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Richard P Fox (American Psychoanalytic Association) on Sept 13 article on decision to bar three psychiatrists from testifying against former patient charged with murder cites 1996 Supreme Court ruling upholding privilege of psychotherapist-patient relationship</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Judge Bars Testimony of 3 Psychiatrists in Murder Case'' (news article, Sept. 13):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Judge Bars Testimony of 3 Psychiatrists in Murder Case'' (news article, Sept. 13):</p>
        <p>You report that Judge Leslie Crocker Snyder of Manhattan Criminal Court, in upholding the privilege of the psychotherapist-patient relationship, said she had to balance the court's ''truth-finding function'' against protections similar to those that exist between a lawyer and his client.</p>
        <p>In 1996, the Supreme Court ruled against a balancing component in judicial hearings, stating that the psychotherapist privilege ''serves the public interest by facilitating the provision of appropriate treatment for persons suffering the effects of a mental or emotional problem.''</p>
        <p>The emphasis in the Supreme Court's decision is critical in insuring the confidentiality of psychotherapy against ''competing interests.''</p>
        <p>RICHARD P. FOX, M.D.  President, American  Psychoanalytic Association  Dana Point, Calif., Sept. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
